\begin{remark}
The proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:splitting} has an interesting consequence. Namely, assume that~$L=L^{(0)},L^{(1)},\dots,L^{(s)}=L_1\sqcup\dots\sqcup L_\mu $ is a splitting sequence
for which there exists~$\omega\in\mathbb{T}_*^\mu$ and~$\varepsilon=\pm 1$ such that the following holds: for each~$i$,
either~$\sigma_{L^{(i+1)}}(\omega)=\sigma_{L^{(i)}}(\omega)+\varepsilon$, or~$\eta_{L^{(i+1)}}(\omega)=\eta_{L^{(i)}}(\omega)+1$. Then, this splitting sequence is minimal. This proof also shows that our bound has the same parity as the splitting number.
\end{remark}

\begin{remark}
In the case of an ordered link~$L$ and for generic~$\omega$, Theorem~\ref{thm:splitting} can also be proved by using~$4$-dimensional considerations. Indeed,
a splitting sequence of length~$s$ provides an immersed concordance in~$S^3\times[0,1]$ between~$L$ and the corresponding split link, with~$s$ transverse double points.
Removing~$B^3\times[0,1]$, where~$B^3$ is a~$3$-ball in~$S^3$ that meets each component of~$L$ in a small unknotted arc untouched by the crossing changes,
we obtain a collection of discs in~$B^4$ with~$s$ double points, bounding the link~$L\#\overline{L_1}\#\dots\#\overline{L_\mu}$. The result then follows from Theorem~7.2,
Proposition~2.10 and Proposition~2.12 of~\cite{CF}.
\end{remark}

